ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Wild yam (_Dioscorea hispida_ Dennst.), also known in some areas as
'nami,' 'kayos,' 'kuyot,' and 'kurot,' is a close relative of better
known yam varieties such as 'ubi' and 'tugui.' It thrives well under
adverse environmental conditions and grows abundantly in most
Philippine forests and hillsides.

This wild yam is not the same as what many of us know as yams or
sweet potato which is _Ipomoea batatas_.

However, wild yam contains dioscorine, a known alkaloid causing
central nervous system depression. The alkaloid is similar in action
to picrotoxin. Hence, for human consumption proper detoxification of
this root crop is required. Researchers of the Leyte State University
(LSU) in Baybay, Leyte developed 2 methods of wild yam detoxification
a reduced time and cost.

The traditional method involves soaking it in water with sawdust for
several days.

This wild yam is not the same as the cassava root _ Manihot
esculenta_. This plant contains a cyanogenic glucoside. Pictures of
the plant and the root may be found at:
<http://www.rain-tree.com/Plant-Images/dioscorea-pic.htm>.

Portions of this comment were extracted from:
<http://www.pcarrd.dost.gov.ph/news/Aug2002/news&events82-22.htm>. - Mod.TG]
